  <h2>Why RV Water Filtration Is Essential</h2>
  <p>Full-time RVers and frequent travelers face a unique water quality challenge: inconsistency. Unlike a permanent home connected to a single municipal supply, RV life means connecting to a new water source at every campground, RV park, or dump station. Each connection brings different water chemistry, different infrastructure age, and different contaminant profiles.</p>
  <p>We have personally measured TDS levels at campgrounds ranging from 40 ppm (excellent) to over 600 ppm (undrinkable without treatment) within a single state. Some campgrounds have brand-new infrastructure delivering pristine water. Others rely on decades-old pipes, aging wells, or water systems that were never designed for the number of connections they now serve.</p>
  <p>Beyond the external water source, your RV's own plumbing introduces risks. Fresh water tanks develop biofilm if not sanitized regularly. Hoses sitting in the sun breed bacteria. And RV plumbing fixtures are not held to the same lead-free standards as residential plumbing. Filtration at the point of use is the only way to ensure consistently clean drinking water regardless of where you park.</p>

  <h2>What to Look For in an RV Water Filter</h2>
  <p>RV water filtration works best as a two-stage approach: pre-filtration at the hookup and point-of-use filtration for drinking water.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Inline sediment pre-filter:</strong> Connects between the campground spigot and your RV. Removes sand, rust, and debris that would otherwise enter your tank and damage plumbing. Standard 10-inch housings with 5-micron cartridges are the norm.</li>
    <li><strong>Compact footprint:</strong> RV counter space and storage are limited. Your drinking water filter needs to be small enough to fit alongside other kitchen essentials. Countertop RO units and pitchers work best.</li>
    <li><strong>No permanent installation:</strong> Many RVers prefer systems they can set up and break down easily. Countertop RO systems plug in and sit on the counter — no drilling or plumbing modifications needed.</li>
    <li><strong>Vibration tolerance:</strong> RV components get bounced around on the road. Choose filters with solid construction that handle the vibration and movement of travel without loosening connections or cracking housings.</li>
    <li><strong>Dual-power compatibility:</strong> If you boondock, consider whether your filtration system works on limited battery power or requires shore power. Countertop RO systems need a standard outlet, which works on inverter power when dry camping.</li>
  </ul>

  <ProTip title="The Two-Stage RV Water Strategy">
    Install a sediment pre-filter inline on your water hookup hose to protect your entire RV plumbing system. Then use a countertop RO system at the kitchen for drinking water. This two-stage approach costs under $350 total and provides the same water quality you would get from an expensive whole-house system in a stick-built home. The sediment filter protects your investment; the RO system protects your health.
  </ProTip>

