  <h2>RV Water System Maintenance Tips</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Sanitize your fresh water tank every 6 months:</strong> Use 1/4 cup of unscented bleach per 15 gallons of capacity. Fill, run through all faucets, wait 12 hours, then flush with fresh water until the chlorine smell is gone.</li>
    <li><strong>Use a dedicated white drinking water hose:</strong> Never use a garden hose (which may contain lead) for potable water. White or blue RV-rated hoses are designed for drinking water and cost under $20.</li>
    <li><strong>Drain your system when not in use:</strong> Stagnant water breeds bacteria. If your RV sits for more than a week, drain the fresh water tank and open low-point drains.</li>
    <li><strong>Test each new campground's water:</strong> Carry a TDS meter ($10-15) and test every new water source before drinking. A reading over 500 ppm warrants extra filtration caution.</li>
    <li><strong>Protect hoses from heat:</strong> UV exposure degrades hose material and promotes bacterial growth. Keep your water hose shaded or covered when connected at a campsite.</li>
  </ul>

